  <!-- FAQ -->
  <div class="sec-mark" id="faq-section">FAQ</div>
  <div class="prose"><h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2></div>
  <div class="faq-list">
    <details class="sa-faq"><summary>What is Shopify server-side tracking and how does it work?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>Shopify server-side tracking sends purchase events directly from your server to ad platforms (Meta, Google, TikTok) without going through the customer&rsquo;s browser. When a Shopify order is paid, a webhook fires to Make.com which routes the event to each platform&rsquo;s API endpoint &mdash; bypassing iOS restrictions, ad blockers, and cookie limitations. It works alongside your existing browser pixel, not instead of it.</p></div></details>
    <details class="sa-faq"><summary>Do I need to remove my browser pixel when setting up server-side tracking?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>No &mdash; keep your browser pixel running alongside server-side tracking. The pixel captures upper-funnel events (ViewContent, AddToCart, InitiateCheckout) that server webhooks don&rsquo;t cover since they only fire on confirmed payment. Set a matching event_id in both your pixel and server events so each platform deduplicates and you see one conversion, not two.</p></div></details>
    <details class="sa-faq"><summary>How much of my lost Shopify conversion data will server-side tracking recover?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>Most Shopify stores recover 20&ndash;40% of previously invisible conversions after deploying server-side tracking. TikTok&rsquo;s own data shows a 19% average increase in attributed events. The exact figure depends on your traffic mix &mdash; stores with high iOS and mobile traffic typically see higher recovery rates. The gap between your Shopify dashboard and ad platform reports should narrow significantly within 24&ndash;72 hours.</p></div></details>
    <details class="sa-faq"><summary>Is server-side tracking GDPR compliant?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>The data flows through your own Make.com workspace &mdash; you control what is sent and can delete the scenario at any time. All personally identifiable information (email, phone) is SHA-256 hashed before transmission as required by each platform&rsquo;s API specification. Ensure your store privacy policy discloses server-side conversion data sharing with advertising platforms. For GDPR-specific advice consult a legal professional.</p></div></details>
    <details class="sa-faq"><summary>How long before I see results after setting up server-side tracking?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>Server events start flowing immediately after your first paid order. More conversions will appear in your ad platform reporting within 24&ndash;48 hours. Meaningful CPA and ROAS improvement typically takes 7&ndash;14 days as ad platform algorithms recalibrate delivery optimisation using the more complete conversion signal.</p></div></details>
    <details class="sa-faq"><summary>How often does Make.com&rsquo;s free tier actually fail or rate-limit?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>The Make.com free plan limit is 1,000 operations per month, refreshing on the 1st of each month. One Shopify order = 3 operations (Meta + Google + TikTok), so the free tier handles ~330 orders/month before hitting the cap. Make.com does not &ldquo;fail&rdquo; mid-month &mdash; it pauses your scenario and emails you. Real failure modes are different: a temporary Meta API outage, an expired access token, or a malformed payload. These are caught in Make.com&rsquo;s execution log under each scenario, and re-runs are free.</p></div></details>
    <details class="sa-faq"><summary>Will server-side tracking still work after iOS 19 ships in 2026?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>Yes. Server-side tracking is specifically designed to be immune to iOS browser-level restrictions because the event originates from Shopify&rsquo;s server, not the customer&rsquo;s iPhone. iOS 19 is widely expected to extend Link Tracking Protection and tighten Safari&rsquo;s Intelligent Tracking Prevention further &mdash; both of which only affect browser pixels. CAPI, Google Enhanced Conversions, and TikTok Events API will continue to function exactly as documented. If anything, server-side tracking becomes more valuable with each iOS release.</p></div></details>
    <details class="sa-faq"><summary>Do I still need server-side tracking if I&rsquo;m using Shopify&rsquo;s native Customer Events / Web Pixels?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>Yes. Shopify&rsquo;s Web Pixels framework is still browser-based &mdash; it loads in a sandboxed iframe in the customer&rsquo;s browser and is subject to the same ad blocker and ITP restrictions as a regular pixel. It improves reliability slightly versus a raw Meta Pixel install, but does not match the recovery rate of a true server-side webhook firing from Shopify&rsquo;s backend on confirmed payment. Run Web Pixels for upper-funnel events (PageView, AddToCart) and the Make.com webhook method for the Purchase event.</p></div></details>
    <details class="sa-faq"><summary>What is the difference between Meta CAPI and Shopify&rsquo;s native data sharing?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>Shopify&rsquo;s native Maximum data sharing setting enables their own CAPI integration, but it is still partially browser-triggered &mdash; if the thank-you page pixel fails to execute, the server event may not fire. The Make.com webhook method fires directly from Shopify&rsquo;s backend on payment confirmation with zero browser dependency, making it more reliable.</p></div></details>
    <details class="sa-faq"><summary>Can I set up Shopify server-side tracking without a developer?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>Yes. The Make.com webhook setup requires no code. You configure a Shopify webhook in Settings, build an HTTP module in Make.com&rsquo;s visual drag-and-drop interface, and paste your API credentials. Most store owners complete the setup in under 20 minutes. No developer, no agency, no Shopify app installation required.</p></div></details>
    <details class="sa-faq"><summary>Does server-side tracking work with Shopify&rsquo;s native Maximum data sharing?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>Yes &mdash; the Make.com webhook method works independently of and alongside Shopify&rsquo;s native data sharing. You do not need to disable native CAPI. Running both adds redundancy: if one delivery method has a transient failure, the other ensures the event still reaches the platform. Use matching event_id values in both so platforms deduplicate correctly.</p></div></details>
    <details class="sa-faq"><summary>How much does Shopify server-side tracking cost?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>The Make.com webhook method costs &pound;0/month for Shopify stores under approximately 250 orders per month, since each order consumes 3 Make.com operations (one per platform: Meta, Google, TikTok) and the free tier covers 1,000 operations monthly. Above 250 orders/month, the Make.com Core plan at $9/month covers 10,000 operations &mdash; sufficient for stores up to roughly 3,300 orders/month. Managed alternatives like Elevar (&pound;400&ndash;&pound;2,000/month) and Triple Whale (&pound;100&ndash;&pound;400/month) achieve the same tracking quality at significantly higher cost. The premium pays for managed onboarding and dashboards, not for superior API access.</p></div></details>
    <details class="sa-faq"><summary>What Event Match Quality (EMQ) score is good for Meta CAPI on Shopify?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>Meta scores Event Match Quality from 1 to 10. For Shopify stores using the Make.com webhook method, EMQ 7&ndash;8 is the realistic ceiling and represents very good performance &mdash; achieved by sending hashed email, phone, zip, IP, user agent, <code>fbc</code> and <code>fbp</code>. Scores of 9&ndash;10 are excellent but typically require logged-in customer data with full address fields. Anything below 5 indicates missing match keys: investigate email format (lowercase + trim before SHA-256), phone format (E.164 digits-only before SHA-256), and the <code>external_id</code> field (Shopify <code>customer.id</code>, hashed). Stores at EMQ 8+ consistently report 12&ndash;28% lower cost-per-purchase than equivalent stores at EMQ 5&ndash;6.</p></div></details>
    <details class="sa-faq"><summary>Why is my TikTok event match quality low even with server-side tracking?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>The single most common cause is sending the event name &ldquo;Purchase&rdquo; instead of <code>CompletePayment</code>. TikTok&rsquo;s Events API requires <code>CompletePayment</code> as the event name for purchase events &mdash; sending &ldquo;Purchase&rdquo; (which works for Meta) results in low Event Match Score and prevents purchase-campaign optimisation. Other common causes: missing hashed email, missing IP address (you must map <code>order.client_details.browser_ip</code> from the Shopify webhook payload, not the Make.com runtime IP), missing TikTok Click ID (<code>ttclid</code>) for paid traffic, and missing user agent. Sending all four high-impact signals (email, phone, IP/UA, external_id) typically lifts TikTok Event Match Score to 80&ndash;100.</p></div></details>
  </div>

